The gun wasn't loaded.
My father took it from me and pulled me into a hug while I began bawling. He said I did good, and told me he didn't want that to be the last way I saw of him.
When I calmed down, I hugged my dog again and then ran into the house. I heard the gun as I closed the door, and an hour later my father returned covered in dirt.
He never told me why he did it. I never asked. He passed away a few years ago from a stroke in his sleep.
I loved my dog very much, and I loved my father.
